    <section id="tailwind-scott">
      <h2 class="font-extrabold text-xl">
        <a href="#tailwind-scott">Tailwind Labs + Scott</a>
      </h2>
      <p class="my-4">
      I feel energized reading the application for this position. My interest in Tailwind CSS as a company has grown ever since I started using it a <a class="link" href="https://github.com/kingscott/kingscott.github.io/commit/37b172b22bf5913bd4ae2c931410fe1d2593cedb#diff-0eb547304658805aad788d320f10bf1f292797b5e6d745a3bf617584da017051" target="_blank">few years ago</a>. Plus, I re-read and share the importance of <a class="link" href="https://adamwathan.me/css-utility-classes-and-separation-of-concerns/" target="_blank">utility classes</a> often. It'd be a dream come true to work at a company where you've been a user and advocate of the product for awhile!  
      </p>
      <p class="my-4">
      At my current company, SugarCRM, I operate in a visible part of the organization where I'm often encouraged to use my influence as leverage to help steer technical decisions, and aid fellow engineers in their work. Introducing Tailwind CSS to our core platform was no exception. We needed to shift gears from our style pipeline growing linearly with every new feature, to a lean, mean, and reusable toolset that enabled our engineers.     
      </p>
      <p class="my-4">
      That change couldn't happen overnight; not only is our codebase shared and large, but there are nuances to our quarterly release cycle, especially with on-premise customers. We'd even need to consider external developers that build on top SugarCRM by way of our customization framework. I started laying the foundations for Tailwind CSS adoption almost 2 years prior, with a set of mixins to generate utility classes. Therefore, we could introduce them as needed, and shift our approach to styling as well. One of them to generate classes like <code class="text-red-600">`ml-4`</code> looked like this:        
      </p>
      <div class="bg-slate-900 font-mono leading-relaxed p-10 rounded-lg text-sm text-neutral-100 w-full">
        <div>.generate-rem-utility-class(@props, @abbreviation, @n, @p, @hasNegativeValues) {</div>
        <div class="pl-4">.-(@i: length(@n)) when (@i > 0) {</div>
        <div class="pl-8">@class-name: extract(@n, @i);</div>
        <div class="pl-8">@current-value: extract(@p, @i);</div>
        <div class="pl-8">.@{abbreviation}-@{class-name} {</div>
        <div class="pl-12">.-(@j: length(@props)) when (@j > 0) {</div>
        <div class="pl-16">@current-prop: extract(@props, @j);</div>
        <div class="pl-16">@{current-prop}: (@current-value / 4) * 1rem;</div>
        <div class="pl-16">.-(@j - 1);</div>
        <div class="pl-12">}</div>
        <div class="pl-12">.-;</div>
        <div class="pl-8">}</div>
        <div class="pl-8">.-@{abbreviation}-@{class-name} when (iskeyword(@hasNegativeValues) = true) {</div>
        <div class="pl-12">.-(@k: length(@props)) when (@k > 0) {</div>
        <div class="pl-16">@current-prop-neg: extract(@props, @k);</div>
        <div class="pl-16">@{current-prop-neg}: (@current-value / 4) * -1rem;</div>
        <div class="pl-16">.-(@k - 1);</div>
        <div class="pl-12">}</div>
        <div class="pl-12">.-;</div>
        <div class="pl-8">}</div>
        <div class="pl-8">.-(@i - 1);</div>
        <div class="pl-4">}</div>
        <div class="pl-4">.-;</div>
        <div>}</div>
        <div class="pt-8">@names: "1", "2", "3";</div>
        <div>@values: "0.25", "0.5", "0.75";</div>
        <div>.generate-rem-utility-class(margin-left, ml, @names, @values, 1);</div>
      </div>
      <p class="my-4">
      Ultimately, we made the transition and removed the old utilities this year. Everyone loves the cleanliness it brought to our codebase, and the ease of writing new styles. I'd be remiss if I didn't mention that I wrote a small announcement on our developer blog for how external developers can join in on the fun: 
      </p>
      <figure class="flex items-center justify-center my-4 w-full">
        <div class="bg-white flex flex-col p-8 rounded-lg shadow-xl xs:w-full md:w-2/3">
